with the following `ComputeInterpolant` function added to InterpolationContext.java:
```java
public Expr[] ComputeInterpolant(Expr pat)
{
	checkContextMatch(pat);

	Params p = mkParams();

	Native.LongPtr n_i = new Native.LongPtr();
	Native.LongPtr n_m = new Native.LongPtr();
	int r = Native.computeInterpolant(nCtx(), pat.getNativeObject(), p.getNativeObject(), n_i, n_m);
	ASTVector seq = new ASTVector(this, n_i.value);
	int n = seq.size();
	Expr[] res = new Expr[n];
	for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
		res[i] = Expr.create(this, seq.get(i).getNativeObject());
	return res;
}
```
When I run this function, the interpolant given is `(= |#PC'| 1)`, but as the output at the end of the function proves, `B -> not(I)` is not a tautology, hence the interpolant is wrong.

## Remaining thunkservables to convert to epics

* [x] `save` #599
* [x] `saveAs` #599 
* [x] `newKernel` #605
* [x] `setNotebook` #609
* [x] `executeCell` #611

--------------------

redux-observable [switched to using Epics over thunkservables](http://redux-observable.js.org/docs/FAQ.html#why-were-thunkservables-deprecated) a little while back. We've since added [fairly decent docs](http://redux-observable.js.org/docs/basics/Epics.html) on these. Epics are a function that takes a stream of actions in and returns a stream of new actions out. The tl;dr is that instead of dispatching a thunk that returns an observable, you dispatch regular POJO actions and listen for them in process managers called Epics which can then do your side effects in response and then they emit other actions when they're done with any response or signal.

I briefly looked through the nteract source and found two thunkservables as examples, [save/saveAs](https://github.com/nteract/nteract/blob/master/src/notebook/actions/index.js#L57).

They would be ported over to something _like_ this (untested...sorry!):

```js
// Extracted out for readability, but you don't have to or you can use
// something like the rxjs-fs package
const writeFileObservable = (filename, data, ...args) =>
  Observable.create(observer => {
    fs.writeFile(filename, data, ...args), error => {
      if (error) {
        observer.error(error);
      } else {
        observer.next({ filename, data });
        observer.complete();
      }
    });
  });

const SAVE = 'SAVE';
const SAVE_AS = 'SAVE_AS';

const changeFilename = filename => ({ type: CHANGE_FILENAME, filename });
const save = (filename, notebook) => ({ type: SAVE: filename, notebook });
const saveAs = (filename, notebook) => ({ type: SAVE_AS: filename, notebook });
const doneSaving = () => ({ type: DONE_SAVING }); 

const saveEpic = actions =>
  actions.ofType(SAVE)
    .do(action => {
      // If there isn't a filename, save-as it instead
      if (!action.filename) {
        throw new Error('save needs a filename');
      }
    })
    .mergeMap(action =>
      writeFileObservable(filename, JSON.stringify(commutable.toJS(action.notebook), null, 1))
        .map(doneSaving)
        // .startWith({ type: START_SAVING })
        // since SAVE effectively acts as the same as START_SAVING
        // you could just look for that in your reducers instead of START_SAVING
    );

const saveAsEpic = actions =>
  actions.ofType(SAVE_AS)
    .mergeMap(action => [
      changeFilename(action.filename),
      save(action.filename, action.notebook)
    ]);
```

I wish I could port everything over but I lost fairly quickly without diving super deep into how everything works. Instead, I'm happy to answer any questions you all may have and/or actually pair with one of you.

Since thunkservables are deprecated, we'd like to remove support for them ASAP so that people who can use other middleware together with it, like redux-thunk.

As a side note, your existing thunkservables don't seem to `(subscriber|observer).complete()` so the middleware's subscription will never finish so that might be a memory "leak".

